Problem 2: Automatic Histograms (22 points)

As you may have seen in Problem 1A, it can be tedious to figure out what the best number of bins or binwidth is for a histogram. Wouldn’t it be nice if there was an automatic way to choose these things?

In fact, there are many automatic ways to do this! See here for many different “rules” for either choosing the number of bins \(k\) or the binwidth \(h\). We will consider the following rules:

  • Sturges’ formula (which gives you the number of bins)
  • The Rice rule (which gives you the number of bins)
  • Scott’s rule (which gives you the binwidth)
  • Freedman-Diaconis’ rule (which gives you the binwidth)

All of these rules are described on the Wikipedia page linked above. In fact, the hist() function (how you can make a histogram in R without ggplot()) already has the first, third, and fourth rules available. Unfortunately, these rules are not readily available in ggplot; however, they can be readily coded up, which is what you’ll have to do in this problem.

  1. (12pts) In this part, write four functions:
  • getSturgesBinNum(x): Returns the number of bins according to Sturges’ rule.
  • getRiceBinNum(x): Returns the number of bins according to the Rice rule.
  • getScottsBinwidth(x): Returns the binwidth according to Scott’s rule.
  • getFDBinwidth(x): Returns the binwidth according to Freedman-Diaconis’ rule.

Each of these functions should take in a quantitative vector x (e.g., songs$YEAR). To get you started, there is some template code below that you can edit. After you’ve written your functions, report what each function returns when you input songs$YEAR. Here are a few other hints to help you with this problem:

  • Sturges’ rule and the Rice rule involve the ceiling function; the ceiling function in R is ceiling(x).
  • The Rice rule and Scott’s rule involves the cubic root; note that \(\sqrt[3]{n} = n^{1/3}\), which you can type in R.
  • Sturges’ rule also uses the \(\log_2(x)\) function; this is log2(x) in R.
  • Freedman-Diaconis’ rule involves the IQR, which you can compute using the IQR() function.

To be clear, this problem requires minimal coding; each function only requires 3-4 lines of code (some of which I already give you in the template code below). This problem is just meant to demonstrate that sometimes we can write mini functions to help us make graphs (as we will see in Part B). Remember to report what the each function returns when you input the songs$YEAR variable!

#TEMPLATE CODE - MODIFY THIS
getSturgesBinNum = function(x){
    #number of observations
    n = length(x)
    #thus, the number of bins is
    k = ceiling(log2(n)) + 1
    return(k)
}
#TEMPLATE CODE - MODIFY THIS
getRiceBinNum = function(x){
    #number of observations
    n = length(x)
    #thus, the number of bins is
    k = ceiling( 2*(n^(1/3)) )
    return(k)
}
getScottsBinwidth = function(x){
    #the standard deviation is
    sigma = sd(x)
    #number of observations
    n = length(x)
    #thus, the binwidth is
    h = (3.49*sigma)/(n^(1/3))
    return(h)
}
getFDBinwidth = function(x){
  #the IQR is
    iqr = IQR(x)
    #number of observations
    n = length(x)
    #thus, the binwidth is
    h = (2*iqr)/(n^(1/3))
    return(h)
}
# REPORT WHAT YOU GET FOR EACH OF THESE FUNCTIONS HERE
getSturgesBinNum(songs$YEAR)
## [1] 11
getRiceBinNum(songs$YEAR)
## [1] 20
getScottsBinwidth(songs$YEAR)
## [1] 5.46093
getFDBinwidth(songs$YEAR)
## [1] 4.008032

We see that our getSturgesBinNum() function gave us an output of 11 bins, whereas getRiceBinNum() gave an output of 20 bins (almost double). Meanwhile, our getScottsBinwidth() function gave us an output of a 5.46 binwidth, and our getFDBinwidth() function gave us an output of a 4.01 binwidth.

  1. (10pts) Now make a histogram of songs$YEAR using each of the four rules from Part A. Specifically, make these four histograms:
  • A histogram of songs$YEAR, specifying bins using Sturges’ rule.
  • A histogram of songs$YEAR, specifying bins using the Rice rule.
  • A histogram of songs$YEAR, specifying binwidth using Scott’s rule.
  • A histogram of songs$YEAR, specifying binwidth using Freedman-Diaconis’ rule.

Make these histograms using ggplot, and please place four histograms in a grid by following template code below. Be sure to add appropriate titles for each plot so that it is clear which histogram corresponds to which rule.

After you’ve made your histograms, discuss the differences among the four histograms in 1-3 sentences.

Remember that you need to specify bins for Sturges’ rule and the Rice rule but binwidth for the other two rules!

#PUT YOUR CODE FOR THE STURGES PLOT HERE
sturgesBins = getSturgesBinNum(songs$YEAR)
sturgesPlot = ggplot(data = songs, aes(x = YEAR)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = sturgesBins, color = "black", fill = "lightblue") + labs(title = "Sturges", x = "Year", y = "Count")
#PUT YOUR CODE FOR THE RICE PLOT HERE
riceBins = getRiceBinNum(songs$YEAR)
ricePlot = ggplot(data = songs, aes(x = YEAR)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = riceBins, color = "black", fill = "lightblue") + labs(title = "Rice", x = "Year", y = "Count")
#PUT YOUR CODE FOR THE SCOTT PLOT HERE
scottsBinwidth = getScottsBinwidth(songs$YEAR)
scottsPlot = ggplot(data = songs, aes(x = YEAR)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = scottsBinwidth, color = "black", fill = "lightblue") + labs(title = "Scotts", x = "Year", y = "Count")
#PUT YOUR CODE FOR THE FREEDMAN-DIACONIS PLOT HERE
fdBinwidth = getFDBinwidth(songs$YEAR)
fdPlot = ggplot(data = songs, aes(x = YEAR)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = fdBinwidth, color = "black", fill = "lightblue") + labs(title = "Freedman-Diaconis", x = "Year", y = "Count")
library(gridExtra)
grid.arrange(sturgesPlot, ricePlot, scottsPlot, fdPlot)

We see that—for this dataset—Sturges’ rule gave us the widest bars, whereas the other three rules gave us fairly comparable bar sizes. If we squint, we can see that the Freedman-Diaconis’ rule gave us the thinnest bars, followed by the Rice rule, and finally by Scott’s rule. In general, the overall shape of the distribution appears to be pretty similar regardless of which rule we used, which is reassuring.

Then, using the code below (that you have to modify), define the variable acidity.normDensity, which is the estimated Normal density for volatile.acidity:
#first, define the mean and variance:
mean.est = mean(wine$volatile.acidity)
var.est = var(wine$volatile.acidity)
#then, compute the Normal density
wine$acidity.normDensity = dnorm(wine$volatile.acidity,

Currently, the above code fits a standard Normal density (with mean 0, standard deviation 1), and you need to replace the mean and sd arguments appropriately. Remember that sd is for standard deviation, which is the square root of the variance.

  • Finally, add the Normal density curve to your histogram of volatile.acidity. To do this, first copy-and-paste your histogram code, and then add the line + geom_line(aes(volatile.acidity, acidity.normDensity)).

The distribution of volatile.acidity appears to be unimodal and somewhat right-skewed, where the mode seems to be around 0.5 units.   1. (5pts) Now we’ll formally test whether volatile.acidity follows a Normal distribution. Do this using the Kolmogorov-Smirnov (KS) test. Specifically: Test whether volatile.acidity follows a Normal distribution whose mean and standard deviation are equal to the sample mean and sample standard deviation of volatile.acidity observed in the data, respectively. In your answer, after providing the appropriate code for the KS test, state your formal conclusion from the test.

Here’s the code to run the appropriate KS test:

ks.test(x = wine$volatile.acidity, y = "pnorm", mean = mean.est, sd = sqrt(var.est))
## Warning in ks.test(x = wine$volatile.acidity, y = "pnorm", mean = mean.est, :
## ties should not be present for the Kolmogorov-Smirnov test
## 
##  One-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov test
## 
## data:  wine$volatile.acidity
## D = 0.054662, p-value = 0.0001416
## alternative hypothesis: two-sided

We get a p-value of 0.0001, which is certainly less than 0.05. Thus, we reject the null hypothesis that the data follow this Normal distribution, thereby concluding that volatile.acidity does not appear to be Normally distributed.

Yes - from the graphs, it does appear that the distribution of volatile.acidity depends on the quality of the wine. First, looking at the side-by-side boxplot, it appears there is a negative relationship between volatile.acidity and quality, in the sense that a higher quality wine tends to have a lower level of volatile.acidity. Meanwhile, by looking at the stacked histogram and smoothed density plot, we can see that the distribution of volatile.acidity is fairly unimodal regardless of the wine quality, thereby validating our focus on the center of the distribution from the side-by-side boxplot. Furthermore, from the side-by-side boxplot, we can see that higher quality wines tend to have less spread/variance in their volatile.acidity, but this may in part be due to the difference in sample size, as we can see by the facetted histogram (it seems like most wines are either of quality 5 or 6).
